english:
  title: A Song in Praise of the Sacred Emperor's Ancestral Worship at the Great Temple, with Preface
  author: Lee Gyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your servant humbly witnesses the Sacred Majesty proceeding to offer sacrifice at the Great Temple on an auspicious day, and thereafter ascending the Pavilion of Ritual Phoenix to proclaim a great amnesty. Thus officials and scholars of the realm, robed in white, gather in the imperial courtyard to present songs and hymns, raising their voices in praise of Your Majesty's virtues. As Recorder of the Right, I attended Your Majesty and personally beheld this glorious ceremony. Being myself a scholar, I have ventured to compose this Song in Praise of the Sacred Emperor's Ancestral Worship at the Great Temple, following the manner of those who presented before you. Yet I am filled with shame and awe, scarcely daring to offer it with my own hands. I pray it may somehow reach the ears of heaven. My trembling heart knows no rest.

    The words are as follows:

    Oh, how profound is our Sacred Emperor—
    truly possessed of both civil wisdom and martial valor.
    Heaven's mandate rests upon him,
    the regency passed from his honored predecessor.
    Continuing the enlightened succession,
    he shines forth like the warming sun.
    The myriads of common folk
    raise their songs and join in jubilation.
    All proclaim: "In the age of our Sacred Emperor,
    what thing fails to find its place?
    I till my fields,
    reaping millet and rice in abundance.
    I gather silkworm cocoons,
    unwinding thread upon thread.
    I harvest hemp to soak in the waters.
    When winter comes, I clothe myself thus.
    When hunger strikes, I eat my fill.
    With parents and children beside me,
    and babes upon my knee,
    we feast on the sacred holidays,
    slaughtering swine and roasting lamb.
    What need have we for instruments of joy?
    We drum upon clay vessels!
    Who dares levy unjust taxes
    to impoverish us poor folk?
    Who dares summon us to war
    to recruit us for distant campaigns?"

    The Emperor speaks to his premier:
    "Since I ascended the throne,
    three years have passed.
    Yet I have not made obeisance
    to the ancestral spirits in their sacred shrine.
    Make haste in your preparations—
    when all is ready, report to me."

    The premier bows obediently,
    his back bent in reverence.
    He commands the officials
    to study the ancient rites anew,
    to select the auspicious day.
    At last the jade chariot is readied;
    the eight bells resound in harmony,
    the six imperial horses gallop in unison.

    Arriving at the sacred temple,
    the ruler purifies himself in the inner sanctum.
    At dawn, the offerings are presented—
    the six ritual vessels and eight treasured baskets,
    all the sacred implements of sacrifice.
    What is this "Great Tiger of the Primal Force"?
    It is the horned bull, splendid and mighty.
    Fine jade and silk adorn the altar;
    nothing is left unprepared.

    The dragon-embroidered robes ascend the steps
    with the measured pace of clouds.
    The hundred princes and ministers
    wear their official caps adorned with pearls.
    Ancestors and their descendants
    are arranged in their proper places—
    right for grandson, left for grandfather.
    The ceremonial songs begin,
    the flutes and drums resound,
    and ten thousand dancers perform below,
    waving feathered fans and silken streamers.

    The ancestors feast and grow mellow,
    blessed with manifold blessings.
    What blessing is this?
    That the imperial line endure for ten thousand years.
    The rite concluded, all withdraw with reverence;
    no decree of ceremony has been violated.
    The imperial carriage returns to the palace;
    praises echo through the streets.

    Then the Emperor proceeds to the Gate of Rectitude
    and proclaims his virtuous mandate:
    he loosens the bonds of prisoners,
    he remits the taxes of the people,
    making no distinction between heavy and light—
    all are treated with impartial mercy.
    He washes away the shame of those long condemned.

    The people all declare:
    "Our Sacred Emperor is the father and mother of his people.
    With filial piety he offers to his ancestors;
    thus does he receive every blessing.
    His benevolence extends to all living things;
    his virtue overflows, his grace spreads wide.
    Ah, we elders rejoice
    to have witnessed this day with our own eyes!
    May he reign for a million years,
    holding dominion over all lands eternal."

    Your servant has heard from the ancients,
    and studied the records of old:
    "When a king receives heaven's mandate,
    what use are phoenixes and unicorns?
    Only the people's contentment matters;
    no omen can match such treasure."

    As Recorder, I attended the imperial progress
    and with clear eyes beheld this sacred ceremony.
    I have composed these verses in proper form,
    hoping they may add to the songs of acclaim.
    Alas! What a noble occasion—
    a meeting granted but once in a thousand years!
  footnotes:
    - The 'Great Temple' (太廟) refers to the royal ancestral shrine where official state sacrifices were performed to honor deceased rulers.
    - The 'Pavilion of Ritual Phoenix' (儀鳳樓) was a structure from which the emperor proclaimed edicts and amnesties.
    - White robes (白衣) worn by scholars signified their status as educated officials and literati not yet in high office.
    - The 'eight bells' (八鑾) and 'six imperial horses' (六駿) were ceremonial elements of royal processions, representing cosmic order and imperial majesty.
    - The hierarchical arrangement of 'grandson on the right, grandfather on the left' reflects the proper ordering of ancestor veneration in Confucian ritual.
    - The poem celebrates not merely the ceremony itself, but how the emperor's filial piety and virtuous governance extend blessings to all his subjects.
